Examples (plane curves)
Two lines
The equation of a line in a Euclidean plane is linear, that is, it equates to zero a polynomial of degree one. So, the Bézout bound for two lines is 1, meaning that two lines either intersect at a single point, or do not intersect. In the latter case, the lines are parallel and meet at a point at infinity.
One can verify this with equations. The equation of a first line can be written in slope-intercept form 
  
    
      
        y
        =
        s
        x
        +
        m
      
    
    {\displaystyle y=sx+m}
   or, in projective coordinates 
  
    
      
        y
        =
        s
        x
        +
        m
        t
      
    
    {\displaystyle y=sx+mt}
   (if the line is vertical, one may exchange x and y). If the equation of a second line is (in projective coordinates) 
  
    
      
        a
        x
        +
        b
        y
        +
        c
